   Estus, Steven and Lynam, Donald R. and Peters, Jessica R. and Jiang,
   Yang},
Title = {{Looking for reward in all the wrong places: dopamine receptor gene
   polymorphisms indirectly affect aggression through sensation-seeking}},
Journal = {{SOCIAL NEUROSCIENCE}},
Year = {{2016}},
Volume = {{11}},
Number = {{5}},
Pages = {{487-494}},
Month = {{OCT}},
Abstract = {{Individuals with genotypes that code for reduced dopaminergic brain
   activity often exhibit a predisposition toward aggression. However, it
   remains largely unknown how dopaminergic genotypes may increase
   aggression. Lower-functioning dopamine systems motivate individuals to
   seek reward from external sources such as illicit drugs and other risky
   experiences. Based on emerging evidence that aggression is a rewarding
   experience, we predicted that the effect of lower-functioning
   dopaminergic functioning on aggression would be mediated by tendencies
   to seek the environment for rewards. Caucasian female and male
   undergraduates (N=277) were genotyped for five polymorphisms of the
   dopamine D2 receptor (DRD2) gene; they reported their previous history
   of aggression and their dispositional reward-seeking. Lower-functioning
   DRD2 profiles were associated with greater sensation-seeking, which then
   predicted greater aggression. Our findings suggest that
   lower-functioning dopaminergic activity puts individuals at risk for
   violence because it motivates them to experience aggression's
   hedonically rewarding qualities.}},
