Abstract = {{The amygdala is a highly interconnected region of the brain that is
   critically important to emotional processing and affective networks.
   Previous studies have shown that the response of the amygdala to
   emotionally arousing stimuli can be modulated by sex hormones. Because
   oral contraceptive pills dramatically lower circulating sex hormone
   levels with potent analogs of those hormones, we performed a functional
   magnetic resonance imaging experiment to measure amygdala reactivity in
   response to emotional stimuli in women using oral contraceptives, and
   compared their amygdala reactivity with that of naturally cycling women.
   Here, we show that women who use oral contraceptive pills have
   significantly decreased bilateral amygdala reactivity in response to
   negatively valenced, emotionally arousing stimuli compared with
   naturally cycling women. We suggest that by modulating amygdala
   reactivity, oral contraceptive pills may influence behaviors that have
   previously been shown to be amygdala dependent-in particular, emotional
   memory.}},
